(thirdQuint)CureOne Registry: Advanced Malignancy or Myelodysplasia, Tested by Standard Sequencing and Treated by Physician Choice.

 Every malignancy or myelodysplasia is different on a molecular (genetic) level even in patients with the same diagnosis.

 These differences often give prognostic information, determine what types of treatments are available for a patient, as well as determine outcomes.

 In this registry, the method of identifying the genetic difference of the disease (using Next Generation Sequencing or NGS) is standardized, the treatments received by a patient, and the outcome of these treatments are entered into a database where all identifying information is removed.

 Payers (insurance companies) or others will generally pay for the testing, laboratories will report the genetic information, physicians and eventually patients will report treatments and outcomes.

 This information will then be reviewed frequently and analyzed to find better methods to improve the testing or treatments of disease.

 It is expected that dozens of other trials or registries will eventually be available for participants.

